	<p>
		<term>Section 1: Metals with variable charges</term>
	</p>

	<p>
		All metals can form ions to form ionic compounds. However, for many metals (such as the transition metals) it is unrealistic to expect them to lose enough electrons to achieve the same electron configuration as a noble gas. Instead, these metals will lose fewer electrons in an effort to empty out their outer s or p orbitals, or to obtain other stable electron configurations. Often there are multiple ways for these metals to achieve stable states, and therefore these metals can adopt different charge states. For instance, iron has the electron configuration <m>\lbrack Ar\rbrack 4s^{2}3d^{6}</m>. Iron can empty out its 4s shell, losing 2 electrons in the process, and forming a Fe<sup>2+</sup> ion. Alternatively, iron can empty its 4s shell AND lose an electron from its 3d shell. This results in a semi-stable half-filled 3d shell. In this case, iron has lost 3 electrons, forming a Fe<sup>3+</sup> ion in the process.
	</p>

	<p>
		So which metals have variable charges and which ones don’t? The metals with known charges are listed below:
	</p>

	<p><ol>
		<li>
			<p>
				Metals in group 1 (+1 charge)
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<p>
				Metals in group 2 (+2 charge)
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<p>
				C.A.Z.A.G. metals
			</p>
		
			<p><ol>
				<li>
					<p>
						Cd, cadmium (+2 charge)
					</p>
				</li>
		
				<li>
					<p>
						Al, aluminum (+3 charge)
					</p>
				</li>
		
				<li>
					<p>
						Zn, zinc (+2 charge)
					</p>
				</li>
		
				<li>
					<p>
						Ag, silver (+1 charge)
					</p>
				</li>
		
				<li>
					<p>
						Ga, gallium (+3 charge)
					</p>
				</li>
		
			</ol></p>
		</li>

	</ol></p>

	<p>
		All other metals in the periodic table have more than one possible charge.
	</p>

	<p>
		How are we supposed to know what the charge of a metal is in an ionic compound if it has a metal with variable charges. When naming these types of ionic compounds, we specify the charge of the metal by putting the charge in parentheses as a Roman numeral (see the table below). Importantly, we ONLY do this if the metal in the ionic compound has variable charges. So the name iron (III) chloride is an ionic compound between Fe<sup>3+</sup> and Cl<sup>-</sup>; the (III) specifies that the charge on the iron is 3+. Chloride is in group 17, and thus we can determine that its charge is -1 (because it only needs one extra electron to have a noble gas electron configuration). From this information, we can determine that the formula for iron (III) chloride must be <m>FeCl_{3}</m> because 3 chloride ions would be needed to balance out the charge of the iron.
	</p>

