	<p>
		Likewise, we can figure out the name of an ionic compound that involves a metal with variable charges by figuring out the charge on the metal by looking at the known charge on the anion. For example, if you were tasked with naming the compound <m>SnO_{2}</m>, you’d first need to recognize that tin is a metal with variable charges. In order to figure out its charge, we need to determine that oxide ions have a charge of -2. Since there are two oxides in the chemical formula, the total negative charge is 2(-2) = -4. The one Sn ion must have a positive charge that balances the negative charges from the oxides. Therefore the cation is Sn<sup>4+</sup>. To name the compound, we name the cation along with the charge in parentheses and then we name the anion. So the name of this compound is tin (IV) oxide.
	</p>

