	<p>
		<term>Section 2: Polyatomic ions</term>
	</p>

	<p>
		There are ions (both cations and anions) that consist of more than one atom, and these are called <term>polyatomic</term> <term>ions</term>. These atoms are joined together by sharing electrons (covalent bonds) to form a single unit. This collective unit of atoms contains fewer electrons (if it’s a cation) or extra electrons (if it’s an anion), and thus the entire unit has a charge. We’ll explore the structures of these polyatomic ions later in this chapter. For now, we won’t worry about their structure. Rather we’ll focus on their component atoms and charges alone.
	</p>

	<p>
		Polyatomic ions have names, formulas, and charges that must be memorized. There are some patterns to their naming that become apparent after close inspection, and these patterns will be looked at as a part of the exercises below. The polyatomic ions that you are responsible for knowing are listed in the table below:
	</p>

