	<p>
		We can name ionic compounds that include polyatomic ions by following the same rules that we learned previously: we simply name the cation (with the charge, if needed) and then the anion. So if you have to name <m>NaNO_{3}</m>, you first of all, need to recognize that it’s an ionic compound (because it has a metal and nonmetals). Then you need to remember that sodium has a known charge (because it’s in group 1) and thus we won’t specify its charge in the name. Lastly, you need to recognize that <m>NO_{3}^{-}</m> is included in the formula and is called nitrate. Therefore, this compound is called sodium nitrate.
	</p>

	<p>
		One additional complication that arises when discussing polyatomic ions is that there is one polyatomic ion, ammonium, that is a cation. Thus, we can have ionic compounds that don’t have metals. They will instead have ammonium (<m>NH_{4}^{+}</m>) as a part of their formula. So <m>NH_{4}Cl</m> is an ionic compound that consists of an ammonium cation and a chloride anion. It is therefore named ammonium chloride.
	</p>

	<p>
		Sometimes chemical formulas will require that we include more than one polyatomic ion in order to balance the positive and negative charges. To specify this, the polyatomic ion is put inside of parentheses and a subscript number is written after the parentheses to indicate the number of polyatomic ions present. So if we were making a compound between <m>Cu^{2 +}</m> and <m>NO_{3}^{-}</m>, we’d need two nitrate ions to balance the charge, and the chemical formula would thus be written as <m>Cu\left( NO_{3} \right)_{2}</m>.
	</p>

